<TEXT>
a lawsuit in federal district court faults the 
social security administration for failing to establish a required 
homeless outreach program but the agency insists it has aggressive 
plans to reach the needy 
the lawsuit filed wednesday in us district court for the 
district of columbia charges that the agency illegally failed to 
act on 1987 legislation requiring it to offer grants to states for 
demonstration programs to help the homeless obtain federal benefits 
the suit maintains that thousands of homeless people who are 
elderly or disabled are incapable of applying for the supplemental 
security income benefits to which they are entitled making it 
essential for the government to provide special outreach programs 
ssi provides a minimum income to 45 million lowincome blind 
aged and disabled people maximum monthly benefits are 368 for an 
individual and 553 for a couple this year rising to 386 and 
579 respectively in 1990 
an estimated 25 percent of the nations homeless are mentally 
disabled another 10 percent are physically disabled and 20 percent 
are elderly according to the lawsuit 
the suit was filed by the national law center on homelessness 
and poverty the states of michigan and massachusetts homeless 
washingtonian ramon willis rep fortney pete stark dcalif 
and two local organizations that offer help to the homeless 
social security spokesman phil gambino said the agency had not 
seen the lawsuit and could not comment on it directly 
however he stressed that social security commissioner gwendolyn 
king has been on the job just five months and is committed to an 
aggressive ssi outreach program to both the homeless as well as the 
aged and disabled 
gambino said mrs king had worked with congress to obtain a 3 
million appropriation for a broad outreach program in fiscal 1990 
that will include grants to states this program is not targeted 
exclusively toward the homeless but will include the homeless as 
well as other aged and disabled individuals he said 
congress authorized 125 million for fiscal 1988 and 25 
million for fiscal 1989 for homeless outreach the lawsuit charges 
that the department of health and human services of which the 
social security administration is a part decided on its own that 
congress had made a poor choice and that the outreach program was 
not needed 
the suit said michigan and massachusetts were ready willing 
and able to participate in a program with hhs to reach homeless 
people in those states 
it said willis is entitled to receive ssi benefits but has 
been unable to secure such benefits due to the physical and 
psychological trauma he has suffered as a result of his infection 
with the aids virus 
although he is very interested in applying for ssi benefits 
he knows nothing about the program and has no idea how to go about 
applying 
