<TEXT>
the recent shutdown of the nations only 
producer of purified plutonium for nuclear weapons could last two 
months or longer energy secretary james d watkins says 
in his most specific comments about the rocky flats plants 
outlook since it completed a phased closure of plutonium operations 
earlier this month watkins said wednesday it was too early to set 
a date for restarting the troubled facility 
i hope well be back on in a couple of months he told 
reporters during a break in a hearing on national energy policy 
options 
the indefinite shutdown was considered necessary to review 
safety procedures and to perform an annual plant plutonium 
inventory a restart date is expected to be announced next month 
outside inspectors have raised many safetyrelated questions 
about rocky flats operations in recent weeks the fbi in june 
raided the plant located near denver to search for evidence of 
possible criminal violations of environmental laws 
the plants future is further jeopardized by the accumulation of 
plutonium wastes beyond a 1600 cubic yard limit set by colorado 
gov roy romer the limit is projected to be reached in april 1990 
and rocky flats may have to be closed down then unless watkins can 
find another site to store the excess waste 
in response to reporters questions watkins said the current 
closure at rocky flats would not give him more time to resolve the 
waste storage problem unless the shutdown lasted more than about 
two months that is because the plutonium inventory itself will 
result in more waste than if the plant were operating normally 
watkins said 
its a wash on waste accumulation if the shutdown is for 
two months he said 
if the closure lasts longer the waste problem could be eased 
but watkins has asserted that a lengthy shutdown of rocky flats 
would endanger us national security because it is the only source 
of purified plutonium for warheads 
in a related development wednesday an energy department 
advisory panel told watkins there appears to be acceptable 
confidence that a longdelayed permanent dump for the rocky flats 
wastes can meet national environmental standards 
the waste isolation pilot plant an underground waste repository 
near carlsbad nm is supposed to be the longrange answer to 
plutonium waste disposal but it has been repeatedly delayed by 
political and scientific uncertainties 
the advisory panel told watkins in a letter released wednesday 
that he should go ahead with plans to put limited amounts of 
plutonium waste in the repository for testing purposes as soon as 
he is confident that environmental standards eventually can be met 
watkins has said the new mexico facility will not open at least 
until next july 
</TEXT>
