an independent counsel says he will not seek 
to retry charges of illegal lobbying against former white house 
aide lyn c nofziger now that the supreme court has refused to 
reinstate his conviction 
james c mckay the special prosecutor said in a statement he 
has decided not to proceed further with prosecution of 
nofziger once a top aide to thenpresident reagan 
on monday the supreme court let stand without comment a us 
circuit court of appeals ruling that overturned the conviction 
mckay said his decision was prompted by the lapse of time since 
events involving nofziger and by the appeals courts interpretation 
of the ethics in government act of 1978 
in these circumstances mckay concluded that the substantial 
expenditure of public funds that would be required to reconstitute 
his office and prosecute nofziger further would be unwarranted 
the statement said 
nofziger who served as white house political director from 1981 
until early 1982 was convicted in 1988 of violating the ethics in 
government act 
the legislation imposes a oneyear ban on lobbying former 
colleagues after a person leaves service in the federal 
governments executive branch 
nofziger was sentenced to 90 days in jail and fined 30000 for 
lobbying top presidential aides within a year of his resignation on 
behalf of three private clients the scandalplagued wedtech corp 
a maritime workers union and the fairchild corp 
but the appeals court in a 21 decision overturned the 
conviction last june the court said the indictment should have 
been dismissed because it did not charge nofziger with having 
knowingly lobbied on matters in which white house officials 
possessed a direct and substantial interest 
mckay said he was disappointed the supreme court did not review 
the governments interpretation of the ethics act he said he 
believed the justice department had understood the statute 
correctly while the appeals court wrongly decided to overturn 
the nofziger conviction 
