<TEXT>
the big three tv networks are asking the ac 
nielsen co to change the way it gathers ratings data including 
shortening the use of people meters to avoid buttonpushing 
fatigue among viewers 
the recommendation was contained in a twoyear study released 
wednesday and paid for by abc nbc and cbs 
in a key recommendation the study which cost more than 1 
million calls for a reduction from two years to one the length of 
time viewers involved in nielsens peoplemeter audience sample 
are asked to participate 
the 2yearold system is in 4000 homes it requires each viewer 
in participating households to press buttons on devices that either 
are handheld or atop the tv set the devices indicate who in the 
family is watching and which program is being seen the data is 
translated into ratings which provide the demographic information 
that advertisers seek 
the study said viewers get tired of pushing buttons and that 
such buttonpushing fatigue sets in before the end of the 
twoyear period 
the study by statistical research inc also found a major 
problem in getting households to join the peoplemeter sample more 
than half of those asked by nielsen to participate declined 
i would say unquestionably the cooperation rate is the 
biggest challenge david poltrack cbs senior vice president for 
research 
the report also urged a joint industry study of ways to measure 
viewing by children under 6 and it urged that nielsen appoint an 
ombudsman whose sole job would be to set and monitor research 
standards 
john dimling executive vice president of nielsen media 
research praised the study as an outstanding effort and said 
the key i think is that the system is good but can be 
improved 
the report was prepared for the committee on nationwide 
television audience measurement founded in 1963 by the three 
networks and the national association of broadcasters to study tv 
audience measurement 
