nato leaders today disclosed that arrangements 
are being made for an unprecedented visit by soviet foreign 
minister eduard a shevardnadze to the organizations headquarters 
the move was announced after the 16 foreign ministers meeting 
here set aside a squabble over a turkish port and approved the 
draft of a treaty to reduce western and warsaw pact forces in 
europe 
a nato spokesman said shevardnadze had requested a meeting in 
brussels on monday or tuesday with secretarygeneral manfred 
woerner 
we are now trying to arrange for mr shevardnadze to have a 
meeting said the spokesman robin stafford 
it would be the first visit to nato headquarters by a soviet 
foreign minister the purpose and agenda of the meeting were not 
immediately known he had already planned a trip to brussels to 
sign a trade agreement with the european community 
the initiative originated at a dinner meeting wednesday night 
between secretary of state james a baker iii and the foreign 
ministers of britain france and west germany sources said 
nato and the warsaw pact are moving to complete a treaty to 
reduce their nonnuclear forces in europe the two military 
alliances appear to be moving into a new stage as east and west 
draw closer together 
among the key provisions of the draft are setting a ceiling of 
275000 for us and soviet troops on foreign soil and sharp 
cutbacks in tanks artillery and other nonnuclear weapons 
in vienna where the negotiators are meeting nato presented the 
proposal polish ambassador wlodzimierz konarski speaking on 
behalf of the sevennation warsaw pact said his alliance is eager 
to examine western proposals 
earlier the warsaw pact presented proposals that would reduce 
six categories of weaponry and have an agreement ready for signing 
by next year 
greece had demanded the nato draft explicitly cite the turkish 
port of mersin as subject to the reductions that are to take place 
across the vast expanse of europe the port was used by turkey in 
its 1974 invasion of cyprus 
after several hours of deliberatiion the ministers decided to 
set the dispute aside but also to give greece an opportunity to 
make its case outside the text possibly in a footnote 
it was agreed hurd said that the text should be tabled 
by everybody ie the consensus was maintained 
he said woerner was told to note that there were certain 
matters covered by several articles which required further 
elaboration 
a nato official demanding anonymity said of the dispute it 
was left open it wont be an obstacle to presenting the text 
the ministers wanted to move quickly because the warsaw pact was 
expected to present its version of the treaty by the end of the 
week the current round of negotiations will be recessed dec 21 
for yearend holidays 
at the start of the nato meeting woerner the alliances top 
official urged the western military alliance to maintain a strong 
defense to ensure the spectacular changes unfolding in the east 
remain peaceful 
since august poland has elected the first noncommunistled 
government in the soviet bloc hungary has ousted its hardline 
communist leaders and disbanded the party east germany has lifted 
travel restrictions opened the berlin wall replaced its hardline 
leaders and scheduled free elections and a government dominated by 
noncommunists has taken control of czechoslovakia 
woerner said a solid security base was needed so that no 
government will ever be tempted to resort to force to solve its 
domestic problems 
the twoday meeting of nato foreign ministers is focused on a 
us prescription for an architecture for a new europe that 
would gradually extend natos mission to the political arena 
woerner a former west german defense minister said the 16 
western governments must make arrangements for transition from a 
postworld war ii order to a europe whole and free and to a state 
of peace in europe in which the german people regains its unity 
through free selfdetermination 
baker who outlined the us plan in a speech tuesday in west 
berlin envisions the alliance as a permament monitor of troop 
reductions now being negotiated with the warsaw pact and as a 
mediator in regional disputes 
woerner told the ministers that the alliance must remain in 
place to provide security and stability throughout the long 
period of transition that we are now entering change needs 
stability 
the developments we have seen thus far have been impressively 
peaceful he said but the pressures which might be released by 
longoverdue change could prove explosive 
norways foreign minister kjell magne bondevik cautioned that 
periods of rapid change carry with them the inherent danger of 
instability 
the tasks that face the reformers of eastern europe are 
enormous he told his colleagues 
he said the reforms that have taken place must be consolidated 
it will take time to establish new stable political and 
economic structures he said we have no guarantee against 
setbacks 
us officials said they did not expect bakers plan to be 
implemented at the twoday meeting of the north atlantic council 
the plan is designed to address the possibility of a reunified 
germany anchoring it in a western political and military alliance 
east germany has been moscows staunchiest ally in the warsaw 
pact and the soviet union opposes german reunification 
within nato itself baker is unlikely to encounter any serious 
opposition 
