<TEXT>
the daring escape of three war 
correspondents from a confederate prison 125 years ago will be 
commemorated this weekend in a ceremony organizers hope will also 
focus attention on hostage terry andersons plight 
on dec 18 1864 new york daily tribune reporters albert 
richardson and junius browne and the cincinnati gazettes william 
davis masterminded an escape from salisbury prison after 19 months 
in captivity 
contemporaries referred to their 340mile journey to freedom 
across the blue ridge mountains as the walk of the journalists 
these gentlemen were not unlike terry anderson said mark 
mcdonald the executive director of the historic salisbury 
foundation inc which is cosponsoring the event with the society 
of civil war correspondents they were 19th century political 
prisoners they were imprisoned not because they took up arms but 
because of what they wrote 
anderson the chief middle east correspondent for the associated 
press has been held hostage since his capture in beirut lebanon 
in march 1985 
wherever terry is being held we fervently wish he might find 
some inspiration from the successful struggle of richardson browne 
and davis mcdonald said 
joining the journalists in their escape 125 years ago were 
connecticut merchant marine capt thomas e wolfe and sgt charles 
thurston of the 6th new hampshire infantry 
mcdonald said richardson and browne who were captured during 
the battle of vicksburg in may 1863 were granted special status at 
the prison 
richardson was given the job of collecting usable clothing 
from the dead he said wednesday richardson was given a pass 
that allowed him to go outside the prison walls to perform his 
duties 
the reporters later used the pass to trick the guards and make 
their escape 
the escape itself did not feature any cloak and dagger 
mcdonald said their journey had a lot more daring associated 
with it 
mcdonald said they had a good reason to escape when they did 
the current commander of the prison major john ghee was 
being replaced by general bradlee johnson a strict 
disciplinarian he said they decided to get out while the 
getting was good 
twentysix days later on jan 13 1865 they arrived in 
unionheld knoxville tenn 
within a day of their arrival the tribune which was run by 
staunch abolitionist horace greeley reported their exploits under 
the headline out of the jaws of death 
salisbury prison which was constructed around an abandoned 
cotton mill held more than 10000 prisoners in october 1864 
between that date and february 1865 3419 of its prisoners died 
the prison was destroyed by union cavalry in april 1865 
beginning on friday the escape will be commemorated in downtown 
salisbury with lectures a walking tour living history portrayals 
a banquet and a recreation 
the escape will be recreated saturday at 330 pm the hour of 
the flight 
gerald a regan a copy editor with usa today and us naval 
academy english professor robert madison will portray richardson 
and browne they will also give readings from books the tribune 
reporters wrote about their civil war exploits 
this is not a story of north vs south but of men caught up 
in a war who refuse to accept captivity said regan they would 
be free because they would accept nothing less no matter what the 
odds or dangers 
journalists dont set out to be heroes but heroic efforts are 
sometimes required in the pursuit of the news he said 
among the weekends speakers will be allen ellis an assistant 
professor at northern kentucky university and a descendant of dan 
ellis who helped guide the journalists over the mountains to 
freedom 
</TEXT>
