<TEXT>
antismoking efforts need to target younger 
people who have relatively little schooling because the use of 
cigarettes drops sharply among the bettereducated federal health 
researchers said thursday 
a centers for disease control study said that while other 
factors may influence smoking education is an increasingly 
important one 
a 1988 behavioral risk factor survey of 36 states and the 
district of columbia found that the lesseducated who also tend to 
be of a lower social and economic status are more likely to be 
smokers than are others 
there has been progress in reducing cigarette smoking said 
dr luis escobedo of the atlantabased cdc who analyzed aspects of 
the survey 
but the study shows most of the progress is limited to the 
welleducated he said 
escobedo said the national cancer institute has a program in 
innercity schools working to reduce the odds of children becoming 
regular smokers and private institutes and some state health 
departments do the same 
results based on a random telephone survey of 19822 people 18 
years of age or older showed that for people over 35 the 
likelihood of being a current smoker increased with each decrease 
in the level of education 
however for those age 18 to 34 the chance of being a current 
smoker decreased substantially only for those with more than a high 
school education while smoking rates for high school dropouts and 
high school graduates were more nearly equal 
the study said cultural factors also may affect who smokes for 
example utah which has a high population of mormons whose church 
opposes smoking had the lowest rate of smokers 181 percent and 
former smokers 91 percent 
kentucky a tobaccogrowing state had the highest percentage of 
current smokers at 379 percent the highest percentage of former 
smokers was in maine 203 percent 
the median figure for current smokers was 262 percent meaning 
that half the states were above that figure and half below the 
median figure for former smokers was 151 percent 
the study said other factors affecting who smokes include school 
antismoking programs state cigarette taxes and the intensity of 
promotional events and advertising by the tobacco industry 
the survey was part of a study done annually since 1980 with 
more states participating each year he said 
