a planned agreement between the environmental 
protection agency and the army corps of engineers aimed at carrying 
out president bushs campaign pledge to preserve wetlands may be 
put on hold for 30 days an epa spokeswoman said thursday 
the memorandum of agreement which was scheduled to take effect 
friday has sparked an intense struggle within the administration 
the departments of energy and transportation oppose it and the 
council on environmental quality and the national oceanic and 
atmospheric administration are in favor 
congressional sources who spoke on condition that they not be 
identified also said the interior department has split with the 
fish and wildlife service favoring immediate implementation and the 
minerals management service opposed 
environmentalists are keeping a close watch on the dispute 
which has been growing since epa and the corps initialled the new 
agreement early last month 
i think this is a real litmus test of bushs commitment to 
wetlands protection said jan goldmancarter counsel to the 
national wildlife federations fish and wildlife division 
we feel if the memorandum of agreement is secondguessed by 
the administration now it will signal the end of any real effort by 
the bush administration to reverse the wetlands losses we have been 
experiencing ms goldmancarter said 
alicia tenuta an epa spokeswoman said that while no decision 
had been made on whether to delay the agreement delay was a 
definite possibility 
ms tenuta said that other agencies and the white house have 
been very interested in the agreement 
the white house wants to make clear what this means to 
everyone ms tenuta said sure they had a hand in slowing it 
down and making sure we talked it over with the other parties 
in last years presidential campaign bush endorsed a policy of 
no net loss of wetlands like swamps bogs fens marshes and 
tidal estuaries often craved for residential commercial and 
agricultural development the goal emerged from recommendations of 
the conservation foundation whose then head william reilly was 
appointed epa administrator by bush 
in recent years environmentalists have come to recognize the 
value of these areas for wildlife habitat purification of polluted 
waterways flood control and other purposes 
there have been estimates that as many as 400000 acres per year 
of wetlands were being lost in recent decades 
on wednesday bush signed a bill authorizing 15 million a year 
aimed at rebuilding duck populations by purchasing 2 million acres 
of critical wetlands 
federal law requires that the corps grant a permit before 
developers may put fill in most wetlands epa may challenge the 
decision and has certain veto powers over it and the two agencies 
frequently had been at odds 
under the new memo the corps agreed to strive to avoid 
adverse impacts and offset unavoidable adverse impacts to existing 
aquatic resources and for wetlands will strive to achieve a goal 
of no overall net loss of values and functions 
the memorandum also formally implements guidelines for granting 
permits where an applicant first has to try to avoid hurting 
wetlands and if that fails to minimize the damage 
if the project would still cause significant harm the applicant 
would have to compensate for the loss perhaps by creating new ones 
or restoring old damaged areas 
this memorandum was a clear commitment on the part of these to 
agencies to move forward and protect wetlands said ms 
goldmancarter two agencies that were usually at odds had come 
together 
the agreement has come under fire from the oil industry in 
alaska and the alaska congressional delegation 
their approach to no net loss of wetlands would mean no net 
growth for alaska and its oil industry said sen ted stevens 
ralaska in a letter to white house chief of staff john sununu 
alaska gov steve cowper said in a letter to bush the 
agreement came as quite a surprise and he thought a special 
domestic policy council task force was going to develop a national 
wetlands policy not two agencies 
thursday cowper said alaska would sue if it failed to win the 
changes it wannted in the new policy 
it may make sense in the lower 48 where wetlands are scarce 
but its crazy in alaska the governor said 
