<TEXT>
christine eckermann remembers that in east 
germany you had to tie three christmas trees together to make a 
decent one 
eckermann her friend uwe buschard and her six children have 
few regrets about coming west a month ago 
in good spirits they talk about how theyll bring christmas to 
their temporary home two rooms in a shabby former hotel 
requisitioned for refugees by the red cross 
eckermann and buschard both 30 dont have much spare room in a 
roughly 218squarefoot space they share with three of the children 
at night 
but amid the beds baby crib scuffed hotel chairs and 
bargainbasement wardrobe there will be a tree with ornaments and 
their presents 
were going put in a christmas touch eckermann said 
sitting in the shabby building in a central west berlin residential 
neighborhood where about 50 refugee families live the red cross 
also will be giving out presents 
im not going to be homesick said the former factory 
worker her friend agreed 
a few blocks away west berlins kurfuerstendamm shopping street 
is aglow in ornamental lights a lavish display of wares for west 
germanys traditional season of expensive presents and big family 
dinners 
though eckermann and buschard may not be topnotch western 
consumers yet he has landed an electrical engineering job with a 
monthly takehome pay of about 1100 apart from food and lodging 
provided by the red cross the couple also benefits from west 
germanys generous family support programs and eckermanns alimony 
payments 
i assume if we pay the red cross something for room and board 
it wont be very much otherwise were doing fine she said 
christmas eve has always been a family feast for eckermann and 
shes confident it will remain that way under east germanys new 
travel freedom she said she expects her mother to come over for 
the celebration 
eckermann and buschard packed up the children and moved to west 
berlin the day after the communist authorities opened the berlin 
wall on nov 9 
she and buschard who divorced his first wife in 1984 had a 
fourroom apartment in suburban east berlin but they were not 
happy 
it was on the sixth floor with no elevator no balcony 
cracks in the walls just the way they build in the east she 
said 
no playground just other apartment buildings all around i 
waited seven years to get that apartment 
a strong protestant tradition has survived in east germany 
despite 40 years of communist control with christmas marked in 
public and private as it is in west germany 
but its not quite the same buschard said 
by now stores in east germany dont have presents anymore 
a little chocolate santa claus costs six or seven marks 335 to 
395 then they later rewrap them to sell as easter bunnies he 
said 
packaging for toys is so gray over there added eckermann 
eckermanns children three boys and two girls aged 2 to 14 
are not shy about their wishes sixmonthold samira the couples 
first child sleeps peacefully in her crib 
ronny 11 sporting a new york yankees baseball cap wants a 
bicycle christmas will definitely be better this year he said 
asked why he replied because were in the west thats what 
everyone says anyway 
actually eckermann wants to give ronny his second remote 
control toy car for christmas portable cassette players are among 
the other gift ideas she is contemplating 
the move was tougher on the children than the adults she said 
they left all their toys over there so when they find one 
here in the hall they wont let go 
nearly 320000 east germans have left their country this year 
paired with massive prodemocracy protests the exodus forced major 
political changes in east germany including the opening of its 
western borders 
in west berlin 100 miles inside east germany the arrival of 
50000 east germans has sharpened an existing housing crisis about 
28000 of the refugees are in emergency shelters including school 
gymnasiums and trade fair halls 
we know how hard it is to find an apartment especially with 
six children we just have to deal with that eckermann said 
but well stay in this hotel as long as necessary even if its 
two years 
id rather go to the jungle than back to east germany she 
said maybe if everything changes but not as long as the berlin 
wall stands 
</TEXT>
