<TEXT>
international competition will become an 
increasingly important factor in the success of american 
corporations but some securities analysts are slow to adjust their 
forecasts 
in some instances the business globalization in the 1990s will 
be the biggest factor of all in corporate success or failure with 
brand new markets opening up simultaneously with brand new 
competition 
no previous decade ever has presented such opportunities or 
perils they include the opening of the eastern bloc the advent of 
the european economic community in 1992 and further development of 
the pacific rim nations 
these momentous changes will exert pressure on companies 
throughout the world but they arent the only evolving factors 
less developed nations also are restructuring their economies and 
in fact so is the united states 
stuart robbins research director at donaldson lufkin amp 
jenrette calls it surprising therefore that most wall street 
recommendations and analyses have heretofore ignored many of the 
implications 
one possible reason for this is that the possibilities may be 
too new and complex to deal with the ultimate direction of 
governments in east bloc nations for example is still difficult 
to fathom 
on the other hand those nations together constitute a 
population of more than 400 million people with a desire for more 
consumer goods better housing hotels computer services and 
various components of infrastructure 
robbins says he feels no topic in the next few years will be of 
more relevance to investments or of greater importance to us 
companies than global competition and has advised his companys 
analysts to assume that perspective 
already according to a study by the massachusetts institute of 
technology about 70 percent of american industry is subject to 
foreign competition robbins believes that is bound to increase 
in recent years however a large number of american companies 
have learned how to deal with such competition many have cut 
overhead improved quality restructured operations and refined 
market focus 
already dlj researchers have spotted what they consider to be 
competitive advantages for some american industries among them 
changing technologies could sharply realign overall metals 
production but us minimill and specialty steelmakers should 
remain world leaders in technology and cost 
strong distribution brand recognition and product quality will 
provide soap and cosmetic firms with better than expected global 
opportunities 
us semiconductor concerns will gain considerable competitive 
advantages against japan in developing their positions as primary 
suppliers of proprietary logic components 
us telecommunications companies will begin to expand 
worldwide by selling current capabilities in network designs and 
systems and further developing their growing cellular relationships 
international entertainment will remain an american domain and 
us companies will derive more than 50 percent of their revenue 
from foreign sources 
the opportunities and competition arent necessarily limited 
to large companies small business has become better organized to 
understand and develop new markets in recent years and many have 
learned the techniques of exporting 
michael sumichrast former chief economist of the national 
association of home builders and now copublisher with arthur 
anderson amp co of real estate perspectives a monthly 
newsletter has this to say 
the eastern bloc needs just about everything from auto parts 
to hotels motels roads communication top office space and even 
ministorage 
sumichrast who is familiar with the eastern bloc having been 
born and brought up in czechoslovakia sees a need for a many 
building products ranging from nails to entire prefabricated 
homes perhaps in joint ventures 
yes he says there are problems in doing business overseas but 
then he cites the experience of the head of a small company who 
says he has sometimes found it easier to do business outside the 
united states 
