<TEXT>
thirty graduates of the west point class 
of 1966 died in the vietnam war the most of any class to see 
action in southeast asia 
many are buried beneath two rows of low white stones in section 
34 of the cemetery at the us military academy class of 1966 
is chiseled on each stone bonding the classmates in death as it 
did in life 
washington post reporter rick atkinson has written a book about 
the class of 66 tracing its arrival at the point as freshfaced 
plebes full of kennedyinspired idealism to the idealshattering 
experience of vietnam from postwar career changes to a 20year 
reunion of classmates sharing a fierce determination to honor the 
dead 
the young men of the class of 66 were caught between the 
rapidly changing social and moral values of the 1960s and the 
staunch traditions of a hallowed military academy 
they are a good way of looking at our collective social 
history said atkinson whose book the long gray line has 
made bestseller lists they straddle a kind of fault line of 
american history 
the class of 66 arrived at west point just a month after 
president kennedy delivered a rousing commencement address to the 
class of 62 the words of douglas macarthurs famous duty 
honor country speech delivered a month earlier still echoed 
through west points granite halls 
macarthur told them if you fail the country will be 
destroyed and they believed that said the author in a 
telephone interview during a west coast promotional tour 
atkinson first wrote about the class of 66 while he was a 
reporter for the kansas city times his fourpart series for which 
he won a pulitzer prize in 1982 grew from a conversation with a 
friend who was a 66 west point graduate 
he was talking how they had gone charging off to war and how 
they were going to win the war and come home to tickertape 
parades atkinson said they thought they had a kind of social 
covenant with the country theyd go to west point serve their 
country and in exchange they would be held in high esteem 
instead 66ers who served in vietnam came home to derision and 
distain many were disillusioned about the war and the army some 
questioned whether four years at west point prepared them for what 
they faced in vietnams jungles and rice paddies 
when youre 22 years old you presume yourself to be immortal 
these guys were no different atkinson said some felt west 
point and their army training had not prepared them for combat for 
seeing other men die 
the deaths of two 66 graduates in particular came to symbolize 
the futility and frustrations of fighting in vietnam the first 
died when he tried to pull a soldier out of some mud and the mans 
gun accidentally fired the second was killed along with 41 other 
soldiers when an american jet bombed their hilltop position in the 
midst of a fierce battle 
a hundred 66 graduates were wounded in southeast asia for some 
the tragedy continued after the war atkinson writes of two 
classmates who were murdered one by his business partner and the 
other by north korean soldiers in a border incident over the 
trimming of a poplar tree 
the author follows the odyssey of the class of 66 mostly 
through the lives of classmates john wheeler tom carhart and 
george crocker 
crocker became a career army man leading troops in vietnam and 
grenada in between he helped revive a drugridden demoralized 
army in west germany and served as a west point instructor when a 
cheating scandal and the admission of women sent the academy into 
turmoil in 1976 he is now chief of staff of the 82nd airborne 
division 
wheeler and carhart had both resigned their commissions by 1971 
as had a third of the 579 graduates of the class of 66 
carhart and wheeler also served in vietnam the former in a 
combat outfit and the latter in the rear echelon the two 
classmates clashed after the war when wheeler helped establish the 
vietnam veterans memorial in washington and carhart objected to 
the memorials design calling it a black gash of sorrow and 
shame 
the 36yearold atkinson the son of a retired career army 
officer grew up on army bases a fact that came in handy while 
writing the book 
i feel comfortable around military men he said i know 
they are fundamentally the same as anyone else their hair is cut a 
little shorter if anything else i know the lingo to a certain 
degree i dont now how far it will take you but it will help you 
get a foot in the door 
in 1970 atkinson received an appointment to the west point 
class of 74 but chose to attend college in north carolina to 
study english 
i just decided it wasnt for me he said it was the 
spring of kent state when the war and the army were as unpopular 
as they ever were 
the long gray line has received mostly favorable reviews 
from critics and west pointers both past and present at a book 
signing session this fall at west point a long gray line of cadets 
snaked through the academy bookstore waiting to buy copies and get 
them autographed by the author 
atkinson said he has met or talked to about half of the class of 
66 i keep running into them on the road he said 
some told the author that admitting female cadets and other 
attempts at humanizing west point have devalued the place in 
many ways 
others told atkinson that the intense hazing cadets suffer in 
their first year is juvenile and contrary to what constitutes the 
tenets of discipline 
despite whatever differences or disillusions they may harbor 
atkinson said west point still commands a special place in the 
lives of the class of 66 
most of them feel this great attachment toward west point 
its the fountainhead of their youth as one of them said the 
academy is was and always will be a very big part of their lives 
</TEXT>
