<TEXT>
the head of a major aircraft builder has 
proposed that companies from the united states europe and japan 
join together to produce the next supersonic jets 
jean pierson chief executive officer of europes airbus 
industrie raised the idea for the first time wednesday in a speech 
to an airline industry group airbus based in toulouse france is 
a consortium of four aircraft companies from france britain 
west germany and spain that competes with boeing co and 
mcdonnell douglas corp of the united states 
boeing the largest commercial aircraft maker was caught by 
surprise by piersons remarks 
boeing and other companies have been studying the viability of 
highspeed transport but its too early to tell what kind of 
airplane may emerge from those studies or how it might be 
produced said richard schleh a boeing spokesman in seattle 
certainly international cooperation is one option that merits 
continued study 
officials of mcdonnell douglas werent immediately available for 
comment 
that there will be a son of concorde is beyond doubt 
pierson said referring to the supersonic passenger jets jointly 
built by france and britain when and how is another question 
because of the enormous investment required by such a project 
and the relatively small market for the aircraft the jets should 
be produced in one worldwide program pierson told the wings club 
the most brilliant engineers the superminds from the usa 
europe and japan working together as a team to produce a world 
plane a plane that will shrink our planet further is not a 
utopian dream he said 
he proposed an international consortium based in the united 
states that would bring together us european and far eastern 
companies to produce and market new highspeed jets 
however he warned such a consortium only would succeed as a 
true partnership of equals as in airbus 
if instead one of the participants were to seek supremacy 
over others or were to attempt to divide the others to rule then 
there is no doubt that europe through airbus industrie would have 
no recourse but to go its own way 
there would inevitably then be two supersonic transport 
programs competing fiercely for a limited market 
in response to a question pierson said he hasnt yet discussed 
the sst consortium idea with potential partners however he added 
i intend to be active on the subject 
airbus which has had increasing success in selling jets to big 
airlines around the world now holds an estimated 30 percent of the 
market for commercial aircraft 
the partners in airbus are aerospatiale of france british 
aerospace plc messerschmittboelkowblohm gmbh of west germany and 
casa of spain 
