<TEXT>
the united states has increased protection to some 
domestic industries and added import restraints while pressing for 
eased barriers abroad the group that sponsors world trade talks 
said thursday 
a report by the secretariat of the general agreement on tariffs 
and trade said even though the united states has low tariffs and 
trade impediments in most sectors large trade and current account 
deficits had increased pressure for more restrictions against 
imports 
the report reflected the concerns of many countries over the 
apparent us trend towards bypassing internationally agreed gatt 
procedures and resorting to arbitrary measures to promote its trade 
interests 
the gatt secretariat report formed part of the first evaluation 
of us policy to be carried out under a new trade policy review 
mechanism agreed by ministers in montreal last december 
in a separate report submitted to the gatt council in geneva as 
part of the same evaluation the us government said its trade 
policy was aimed at reducing trade distortions and barriers both 
in the united states and abroad to allow market forces to operate 
and boost trade expansion 
we are totally committed to an open and fair trade 
policy rufus yerxa us ambassador to gatt told the council 
meeting 
those who believe the united states can solve its trade or 
economic problems by erecting high trade barriers are living in 
the age of the dinosaur he said 
yerxa said he regarded the gatt secretariat report as 
generally fair commenting that such an evaluation of trade 
policy was bound to be critical in parts 
a text of his speech was made available to journalists 
a trade source who attended the closed council session said the 
meeting was balanced between criticism and praise for us trade 
policy 
some delegates told the meeting they recognized the us economy 
was open and that it was the largest market for exports from many 
areas including developing countries the source said speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
other participants commended the few import restrictions and 
subsidies outside agriculture he added 
the gatt report said that the high us trade deficits had 
increased popular domestic pressure for increased protection 
it welcomed attempts by washington to resist calls for greater 
import restrictions citing the refusal of the reagan 
administration in 1984 to grant import relief to the copper 
industry and a similar refusal a year later to the footwear 
industry 
however the number of sectors receiving protection and the 
number of restrictive agreements had increased over the years the 
report said listing examples including machine tools and 
semiconductors 
other sectors of the economy such as dairy sugar textiles and 
clothing historically have received relatively high levels of 
protection the secretariat said and little has been done to 
reduce the restraints 
the 97 members of gatt account for more than four fifths of 
world trade 
